The paper proposes a new approach for learning a compact, latent representation of graph structure that is independent of input graph size, while retaining the ability to derive node representations on the fly. This problem is relevant to several sub-fields of computer science, including machine learning (cs.LG), social and information networks (cs.SI), data structures and algorithms (cs.SD), databases (cs.DB), and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also presents experiments on real-world graphs, which suggests that it could be relevant to the sub-fields of data mining (cs.DM) and information retrieval (cs.IR). However, given the focus of the paper on learning a compact representation of graph structure, we believe that the aforementioned five sub-categories are the most likely.
